article.headline: Vanderbilt wins fourth SEC title
article.linkText: Commodores, down 18, right ship against Georgia
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Vanderbilt Commodores had every
reason to quit. Instead, they decided to switch defenses.

Freshman center Carla Thomas had 22 points and 11 rebounds, and Vanderbilt (No. 21 AP) rallied from an 18-point deficit in the second
half Sunday for a 62-56 win over (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) in the championship game of the Southeastern Conference tournament.

"We could've put our heads down and really buried ourselves,
and we didn't," Vandy coach Melanie Balcomb said of her first
championship team.

"I think this team has shown a lot of heart, and I think what
we did tonight just shows what we're made of. I'm excited to take
this team into the NCAAs with that kind of heart and that kind of
effort."

The Commodores (24-7) won their fourth title and first since
2002 despite nearly shooting themselves out of the game in the
first half. The SEC's best 3-point shooters didn't hit a 3 and
scored just 18 points.

So Vanderbilt turned defensive to win its fifth straight NCAA
berth and 17th overall.

Balcomb ditched the zone they were using to slow down Christi
Thomas and Ebony Felder, switching to pressing and trapping. It
helped spark a 21-4 run as Vandy forced 11 turnovers in the second
half.

"They just were willing to make the changes and the adjustments
that we asked them to make. To just mentally throw away that first
half, and that's what we did," Balcomb said.

Georgia looked ready to roll toward its fifth title and first
since 2001, leading 34-18 at halftime. The Lady Bulldogs pushed
that lead to as many as 18 twice in the second half, the last on Thomas' putback with 16:29 left that made it 40-22.

"The splintering began when we were pressed, and we made a
terrible mistake of dribbling the ball over the halfline on the
sideline, and we repeated that mistake at least four times, which
is basically a cardinal sin," Georgia coach Andy Landers said.

"We don't teach it. We shouldn't do it. We did it. We got
trapped."

Thomas led Georgia (22-9) with 17 points. Sherrill Baker
had 16.

Hillary Hager and Dee Davis each scored 11 for Vanderbilt.
Ashley Earley had 10.

Georgia focused on stopping Hager and Abi Ramsey, a pair of 44
percent shooters from 3-point range.

But Hager got Vandy started with its only 3 of the game with
15:34 remaining, sparking the 21-4 run. Carla Thomas, named the
tournament's MVP, capped the run with a putback to pull Vandy
within 44-43, then gave Vandy its first lead since 2-0 with another
bucket to make it 50-49 with 4:13 left.

"You could see fear," Davis said. "It was nice."

Georgia managed to tie it at 54 on Alexis Kendricks' 3-pointer
from the top of the key with 2:33 to go.

But Thomas put Vandy up to stay at 56-54 with 2:08 left,
and the Commodores hit their next four free throws to put the game
out of reach.

"You've got to give credit where credit's due," Christi Thomas
said of the freshman. "She's a good post player, and she's going
to be great by the time she gets out of here."

The SEC's second-best shooting team didn't leave the court
Saturday night until just before 11 p.m., and the late finish
seemed to hurt as the Commodores missed seven of their first 10
shots. Senior Jenni Benningfield bounced a couple jumpers off the
front rim and even missed the basket once.

Carla Thomas had 12 of Vandy's first 14 points.

Georgia had no such problems as the Lady Bulldogs hit 10 of
their first 20. Georgia used a 12-4 run in taking its halftime
lead.
